<br/><!-- hnss:readable-content --><hr/><div id="readability-page-1" class="page"><div><div><p>Now that we know <a href="https://wolchok.org/posts/how-to-read-assembly-language">how to read assembly
language</a>,
we can talk about how parameter passing works at the machine level and
its consequences for writing faster code. We will focus on x86_64, but
ARM64 works in a roughly similar way.</p><p>Let’s say you’ve written a large program, and in it you have two files:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="c++"><span>// Something.h
</span><span></span>
<span>int</span> <span>doSomething</span>(<span>int</span> x, <span>int</span> y);
</code></pre></div><div><pre><code data-lang="c++"><span>// OtherStuff.cpp
</span><span></span>
<span>void</span> <span>doOtherStuff</span>() {
  <span>// ...
</span><span></span>  doSomething(<span>123</span>, <span>456</span>);
  <span>// ...
</span><span></span>}
</code></pre></div><p>The fundamental question of parameter passing is this: at the
assembly language level, what does <code>otherStuff</code> need to <em>do</em> to pass
<code>123</code> and <code>456</code> to <code>doSomething</code> as <code>x</code> and <code>y</code>? There is no single
machine instruction for “call this function with these arguments”;
somebody had to decide how that would work and document the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Calling_convention">calling
convention</a> for
<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/X86_calling_conventions">x86_64</a>!</p><p>On x86_64 Linux and macOS (among other OSes), these decisions follow
<a href="https://raw.githubusercontent.com/wiki/hjl-tools/x86-psABI/x86-64-psABI-1.0.pdf">the System V AMD64
ABI</a>. If
you really want to, you can stop reading now and go read that document
instead. However, it is a long, technical specification and I’ve
personally never read it straight through. In the rest of this
article, I’ll walk through some example code, summarize how parameter
passing works in each case, and talk through the implications for how
you structure your code.</p><p>Consider this function that takes far too many arguments:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="c++"><span>#include</span> <span>&lt;cstdint&gt;</span><span>
</span><span></span>
<span>int</span> <span>takePrimitives</span>(
    <span>int8_t</span> intArg1,
    <span>int16_t</span> intArg2,
    <span>int32_t</span> intArg3,
    <span>int64_t</span> intArg4,
    <span>const</span> <span>char</span> <span>*</span>intArg5,
    <span>int</span> <span>&amp;</span>intArg6,
    <span>float</span> floatArg1,
    <span>double</span> floatArg2,
    <span>int64_t</span> intArg7,
    <span>int64_t</span> intArg8,
    <span>int64_t</span> intArg9,
    <span>int64_t</span> intArg10);

<span>static</span> <span>int</span> x <span>=</span> <span>123456</span>;
<span>void</span> <span>callWithPrimitives</span>() {
    takePrimitives(<span>1</span>, <span>2</span>, <span>3</span>, <span>4</span>, <span>"hello"</span>, x, <span>0.5</span>, <span>0.25</span>, <span>6</span>, <span>7</span>, <span>8</span>, <span>9</span>);
}
</code></pre></div><p>and the corresponding <a href="https://godbolt.org/#z:%2Bd22w0kQPen2GpAhwII/24sJBn14SLQtEak2QCAykwAVHDgABWRHre7I6aSf5k/5UtY0qisVDMHZsjkEUHfan3dA9JzsSbczmg8ECyH0VHo3mfADszJp2zlbwxwEeKt%2BsrRGoVwAAnDqZSj9ci%2Be4OjNZOtNo1OXhkLSAB7TYYAEUmnEkw245P%2Bts251QeHQ%2BLYrAA6oQEMdThcrhAOtNFXaWfd9kcTmc1JdrglJuZJgjJrw6ZIEMp2VIS67SJN3AA6SlN5uSNtMybKybayZGm3DDPiRWegZdVggAbkgakUwDdxz1DTnRyOSTBQ9PqYOnDThzgjTpcdLp7EDDYbNy83293plTgbcOcLpekFcDOcKECeI%2BLiekHAsBIGgRheHg7BkBQECgeBkEoMIoicJw7gJFQEEEK434QE4x5zk4tgZAAntOB6kKBRhaAQADytCsCR/6kFgRgiMA7B4UxeDEMk%2BZXBxmCuskBiYaRc7bMoolCHgTjEMRehYJJBC5qJXQ0PQTBsBwPD8IIiFiOuMhSU436QF0qBeIU34DAAtNRwyTNZCwzJ6EgyHIkhvvkPEBJo2h1KYCSWGUMRxKEvj%2BHQ/lheEATBRU8SJAUqRNFFDRJCkdDFJkcVtAljq1PoOSCPlzTRPFXBdFuvT9BVQjTrO84cR%2BrqPP81moviek%2BpwzYtpwkwQLghAkHuRZ6GBEGuKNqZrm5MiHnhp6kOewz/K2Ro8IqrVGv8ircJwrV1U%2BL5NdOX4/qQf4noBMCICgqATZB5CULBk1uOMrHIahpDoawmHENhuGMQRtDEZJFFUbR9EccxrHsYx%2BDcSkBb8YJyDCYMZHiY%2Bb6sNJsnEER8mDG%2BSmnCpP10IwLDsdpAjmHpKAGfIePGfAZkWQEVm2fZjkEOgzmubIMgeV%2B6WFL5uiFfUFjaDloUJGEEWBNLAXeOFhTy%2B0iXeZlKWq8V4vJSUWt5frwRqyVpu1VVO61Y%2BDWvsu04tW1HUfaI3W9c2/WDfgRDEKNjbjXBU0jJIM3Mwt/5LStLbuIq5IHYqO1GkakjcI8vpHc%2BjWMR%2B52/otk7TpIJ352dl3F6QlwAz53BAA%3D">generated assembly</a>:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="asm">.LCPI0_0:
        <span>.long</span>   <span>0x3f000000</span>                      <span># float 0.5
</span><span></span><span>.LCPI0_1</span>:
        <span>.quad</span>   <span>0x3fd0000000000000</span>              <span># double 0.25
</span><span></span><span>callWithPrimitives</span>():                <span># @callWithPrimitives()
</span><span></span>        <span>pushq</span>   <span>%</span><span>rax</span>
        <span>movss</span>   <span>.LCPI0_0</span>(%rip), %xmm0           <span># xmm0 = mem[0],zero,zero,zero
</span><span></span>        <span>movsd</span>   <span>.LCPI0_1</span>(%rip), %xmm1           <span># xmm1 = mem[0],zero
</span><span></span>        <span>movl</span>    <span>$4</span>, %ecx
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$.L.str</span>, %r8d
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$x</span>, %r9d
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$1</span>, %edi
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$2</span>, %esi
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$3</span>, %edx
        <span>pushq</span>   <span>$9</span>
        <span>pushq</span>   <span>$8</span>
        <span>pushq</span>   <span>$7</span>
        <span>pushq</span>   <span>$6</span>
        <span>callq</span>   <span>takePrimitives</span>(<span>signed</span> <span>char</span>, <span>short</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>long</span>, <span>char</span> <span>const</span>*, <span>int</span><span>&amp;</span>, <span>float</span>, <span>double</span>, <span>long</span>, <span>long</span>, <span>long</span>, <span>long</span>)
        <span>addq</span>    <span>$32</span>, %rsp
        <span>popq</span>    %rax
        <span>retq</span>
.L.str:
        <span>.asciz</span>  <span>"hello"</span>

x:
        <span>.long</span>   <span>123456</span>                          <span># 0x1e240
</span></code></pre></div><p>This lays out parameter passing for primitives nicely. The first 6
integer or pointer arguments (<code>intArg1</code> through <code>intArg6</code> in the
example) go into <code>%rdi</code>, <code>%rsi</code>, <code>%rdx</code>, <code>%rcx</code>, <code>%r8</code>, and <code>%r9</code>, in
that order, regardless of whether they are 1, 2, 4, or 8 bytes in
size. C++ reference parameters are <a href="https://itanium-cxx-abi.github.io/cxx-abi/abi.html#reference-parameters">represented as
pointers</a>. The
first 8 floating point arguments go in registers <code>%xmm0</code> through
<code>%xmm7</code> (here, we use only <code>%xmm0</code> and <code>%xmm1</code>). Remaining arguments
are pushed onto the stack from right to left.</p><h2 id="consequence-consistent-argument-order--position">Consequence: consistent argument order &amp; position</h2><p>Suppose that you have a common series of arguments that you need to
pass to several functions in a row. It would be ideal if those
arguments stayed in the same order and positions:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="c++"><span>#include</span> <span>&lt;cstdint&gt;</span><span>
</span><span></span>
<span>struct</span> <span>Color</span> {
    <span>int</span> r, g, b, a;
};

Color <span>makeColor</span>(<span>int</span> red, <span>int</span> green, <span>int</span> blue, <span>int</span> alpha);

Color <span>makeColor</span>(<span>int</span> red, <span>int</span> green, <span>int</span> blue) {
    <span>return</span> makeColor(red, green, blue, <span>255</span>);
}

Color <span>makeColorBad</span>(<span>int</span> alpha, <span>int</span> red, <span>int</span> green, <span>int</span> blue);

Color <span>makeColorBad</span>(<span>int</span> red, <span>int</span> green, <span>int</span> blue) {
    <span>return</span> makeColorBad(<span>255</span>, red, green, blue);
}
</code></pre></div><p>and the <a href="https://godbolt.org/#z:%2BIJozMADWmD%2BECuN0w6AeEOAxEwWhh9EehkwSOubC8CGY7W%2BG1%2B%2BiOgJBYIh8Ohl2RcIRtHRKIMmHaxzeF0hBB6tABwNBhOIEHJD2piPpaImkgArOLcUM3uJPj8Nn8uSTedJmOhwcjMdi6QLKdchbT9SLpbLFbzlTzWCQ1RqyVC6Ya6U5UUy5SyLvD2cROcSrTb1RAJeKHnqnSa8e8Pv1OqwQP1xf1SKZ%2Bqsk6h4zo5HIJgpur1MFNJENOEmCPG0%2B1OkCQEMhgA6OtN5stgBsQnj3CTKbTpAz/STChAq1I5dTMdIcFgSDQRi8eHYZAoEFn88XKGEok4nFWnFIVAXBFcQ4gTgrSactgyAE946XSLOjFoCAB5WisW/j0hYQGidjn788HhQoADdMCHL9MAADwKAwjzvJMrmUBChDwJxiBvPQsBQghiDwIwEM6Gh6CYNgOB4fhBE3MRsxkVCnCHSBOlQLwUloCCAFoXyGCYOPmdBpg%2BCQZDkSRe3yQoNAgSw6lMPdLDKGI4kEHw/DY2SVPCNjFIqeJFGUAo2OKWp9ByQQJKMxodNaPT5hKDS9zszJrOUzhOjzHo%2Bi4WN40TZMAP7KCAA5Ww41tuAmMYRGACZt3rVZ604CYIFwQgjmGPcDlQOcF1cIsSyZLMRJkMtzyrUgazrRsWxqut2zjfou38r9%2B0HYdRzKycYEQFBsrXVxyEoVdcrcKKtx3PcD1YI9iBPM8v0vWgbxQx9nzfD8AJ/aL/y/fBgLUMCIN7aDYPg/p7yQhre1YNCMOIa8sIGXtcPwwj9zoRgWH/CiBHMaiUFo%2BQboY%2BBmNYgJOO43j%2BME4TZBkMTBwMyTTGk7QHIsbQXLaMI1ICDHVIiWhsds5HLPs0yQkcsmiis5olJxpyskpuTqhKEnvK6TzyJ8hNuwC%2BNgtC8LIuo2LOHixLktSoh/gyh49Byxd8skQrAdK8dysqhtatqjtGv5lr4zakcx0rXnJEN3tWo6zXOjA2aAhAbggA%3D">generated assembly</a>:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="asm"><span>makeColor</span>(<span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>):                        <span># @makeColor(int, int, int)
</span><span></span>        <span>movl</span>    <span>$255</span>, %ecx
        <span>jmp</span>     <span>makeColor</span>(<span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>)                <span># TAILCALL
</span><span></span><span>makeColorBad</span>(<span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>):                    <span># @makeColorBad(int, int, int)
</span><span></span>        <span>movl</span>    %edx, %ecx
        <span>movl</span>    %esi, %edx
        <span>movl</span>    %edi, %esi
        <span>movl</span>    <span>$255</span>, %edi
        <span>jmp</span>     <span>makeColorBad</span>(<span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>, <span>int</span>)            <span># TAILCALL
</span></code></pre></div><p><code>makeColorBad</code> has to shift <code>red</code>, <code>green</code>, and <code>blue</code> to make
everything end up in the correct registers, whereas <code>makeColor</code> just
puts <code>255</code> into the appropriate register and continues on.<sup id="fnref:1"><a href="#fn:1" role="doc-noteref">1</a></sup></p><h2 id="returning-primitives">Returning primitives</h2><p>Returning primitives is even simpler than passing them. Here’s a quick example:</p><pre><code>#include &lt;cstdint&gt;

int64_t getInt();
double getDouble();

void sinkInt(int64_t);
// Primitives should normally be passed by value;
// using reference here because the return register
// for double is %xmm0 and so is the first argument
// register, so the assembly would not show %xmm0 at
// all if passed by value.
void sinkDouble(const double&amp;);

void demonstrateResultReturn() {
    sinkInt(getInt());
    sinkDouble(getDouble());
}
</code></pre><p>and the <a href="https://godbolt.org/#z:OYLghAFBqd5QCxAYwPYBMCmBRdBLAF1QCcAaPECAM1QDsCBlZAQwBtMQBGAFlICsupVs1qhkAUgBMAISnTSAZ0ztkBPHUqZa6AMKpWAVwC2tEJIDMpLegAyeWpgByxgEaZiXAGykADqgWE6rR6hiZmln4BanR2Ds5Gbh6c3koq0bQMBMzEBCHGphaKypiqQZnZBLFOru5eilk5eWGFCg2V9tUJtckAlIqoBsTIHADkUub2yIZYANTi5jrIrfj089jiAAwAgptb9gSe3AD6BDPAmAQAkvQQPfOy2%2BgDLuxnFwAiz%2By397u7AG6oPDoGYBWgAa2uBAg%2B0OJzu5geWwA9MiZgAFYh4IyBf6YBSghADVgg2gkIxsVgATxmbhmPmYCiUIJcNP%2BbAMmF%%2BiUGEUROE4DZOFIT1Z3cAiIBcCC3xcexsipZ9QNIaijEDAB5WhqRE0gsApUR2BU/BhVKPECNIqwrRKAwCFGaT9mUKS31YPAXDHYgqT0LArOIrEjCsvoaHoJg2A4Hh%2BEEdixH/GQhFsgjID6VAfHSfSAFp5PMGY4uWeZ3gkGQ5EkbDUhKdJNG0JpTB46wqniRJBEiQI6CKyr/Gq2gypqJIijSMo2lqnjctKOhyhyJquha1oKk6%%2ByRuFWzgVbQ6GsO/Z94aIkjIPmkZJFT2Gx8Rxu%2Bjxb0ghAbggA%3D%3D%3D">generated assembly</a>:</p><pre><code>demonstrateResultReturn():           # @demonstrateResultReturn()
        pushq   %rax
        callq   getInt()
        movq    %rax, %rdi
        callq   sinkInt(long)
        callq   getDouble()
        movsd   %xmm0, (%rsp)
        movq    %rsp, %rdi
        callq   sinkDouble(double const&amp;)
        popq    %rax
        retq
</code></pre><p>We can see that integer/pointer return values go in <code>%rax</code> and
floating-point return values go in <code>%xmm0</code>.</p><p>Now let’s see how structs work. Here are the different ways we could
pass a 2-dimensional and 3-dimensional integer vector to a function:</p><div><pre><code data-lang="c++"><span>#include</span> <span>&lt;cstdint&gt;</span><span>
